05028nam a22007095i 9780674042070DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740420707 a10.4159/97806740420702doi  a(DE-B1597)574435  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aE18.82 ǂb P47 2007eb 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a973.21 aPestana, Carla Gardina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe English Atlantic in an Age of Revolution, 1640–1661 /cCarla Gardina Pestana. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (356 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Dating and Editorial Method -- tMap: The English Atlantic, 1640–1661 -- tIntroduction: Revolution and the English Atlantic -- tPrologue: The English Atlantic in 1640 -- t1. The Challenge of Civil War -- t2. Puritan Ascendancy and Religious Polarization -- t3. Regicide and Royalist Rebellions -- t4. Religious Politics of a “Puritan Revolution -- t5. Free Trade and Freeborn English Men -- t6. Lost Liberty and Laboring People in the Atlantic World -- tEpilogue: The English Atlantic and the Limits of Restoration -- tAppendix 1. Population Figures, 1640 -- tAppendix 2. London Pamphlets about New England, 1641–1649 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1640 and 1660, England, Scotland, and Ireland faced civil war, invasion, religious radicalism, parliamentary rule, and the restoration of the monarchy. Carla Gardina Pestana offers a sweeping history that systematically connects these cataclysmic events and the development of the infant plantations from Newfoundland to Surinam. By 1660, the English Atlantic emerged as religiously polarized, economically interconnected, socially exploitative, and ideologically anxious about its liberties. War increased both the proportion of unfree laborers and ethnic diversity in the settlements. Neglected by London, the colonies quickly developed trade networks, especially from seafaring New England, and entered the slave trade. Barbadian planters in particular moved decisively toward slavery as their premier labor system, leading the way toward its adoption elsewhere. When by the 1650s the governing authorities tried to impose their vision of an integrated empire, the colonists claimed the rights of "freeborn English men," making a bid for liberties that had enormous implications for the rise in both involuntary servitude and slavery. Changes at home politicized religion in the Atlantic world and introduced witchcraft prosecutions. Pestana presents a compelling case for rethinking our assumptions about empire and colonialism and offers an invaluable look at the creation of the English Atlantic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aBritanniquesxHistoirex17e sièclexAtlantique, Région de l'. 0aBritishxHistoryx17th centuryxAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aPlantation lifexHistoryx17th centuryxAmerica. 0aPlantation lifexHistoryx17th centuryxAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aVie dans les plantationsxHistoirex17e sièclexAmérique. 0aVie dans les plantationsxHistoirex17e sièclexAtlantique, Région de l'. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674042070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674042070/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Back